steps.text:
Consider the function \( f(x) = \begin{cases} 
1 & \text{if } x \in \mathbb{Q} \\
-1 & \text{if } x \notin \mathbb{Q} 
\end{cases} \). This function is not Riemann integrable because it does not satisfy the condition of being bounded on any closed interval and having a set of discontinuities with measure zero. However, \( f^2(x) = 1 \) for all \( x \), which is clearly Riemann integrable. Therefore, \( f \) being such that \( f^2 \) is Riemann integrable does not imply that \( f \) itself is Riemann integrable.

