Substituting these into the integral, we get:
\[
\int_0^{2\pi} \frac{\cos(\theta)}{5 - 3\cos(\theta)} \, d\theta = \oint_{|z|=1} \frac{\frac{1}{2}\left(z + \frac{1}{z}\right)}{5 - 3\left(\frac{1}{2}\left(z + \frac{1}{z}\right)\right)} \frac{dz}{iz}
\]
Simplify the integrand:
\[
= \oint_{|z|=1} \frac{\frac{1}{2}\left(z + \frac{1}{z}\right)}{5 - \frac{3}{2}\left(z + \frac{1}{z}\right)} \frac{dz}{iz}
= \oint_{|z|=1} \frac{z + \frac{1}{z}}{10 - 3z - \frac{3}{z}} \frac{dz}{2iz}
= \oint_{|z|=1} \frac{(z + \frac{1}{z})(z)}{(10z - 3z^2 - 3)} \frac{dz}{2iz}
= \oint_{|z|=1} \frac{z^2 + 1}{-3z^2 + 10z - 3} \frac{dz}{2i}
\]
Thus, the integral becomes:
\[
\frac{1}{2i} \oint_{|z|=1} \frac{z^2 + 1}{-3z^2 + 10z - 3} \, dz
\]

