steps.text:
Now, let's consider the behavior of \(x\) and \(y\) as \(t \to \infty\). The equations for \(x\) and \(y\) form a system of linear differential equations:

\[
\begin{cases}
\dot{x} = -y \\
\dot{y} = x
\end{cases}
\]

This system can be written in matrix form as:

\[
\begin{pmatrix}
\dot{x} \\
\dot{y}
\end{pmatrix}
=
\begin{pmatrix}
0 & -1 \\
1 & 0
\end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix}
x \\
y
\end{pmatrix}
\]

The eigenvalues of the matrix \(\begin{pmatrix} 0 & -1 \\ 1 & 0 \end{pmatrix}\) are \(\pm i\), which are purely imaginary. This indicates that the solutions to the system are periodic and do not tend to zero or infinity. Therefore, \(x(t)\) and \(y(t)\) will oscillate but remain bounded. Let's denote the bounded values of \(x\) and \(y\) as \(x_\infty\) and \(y_\infty\) respectively.

